Some randomization schemes used in power electronics are, [7]–[14]:


■
Randomized pulse position modulation (RPPM): \$\varepsilon_{\rm k}\$ changes; \${\rm F}_{\rm k}\$ and \${\rm d}_{\rm k}\$ are fixed;


■
Randomized pulse position modulation (RPPM): \${\rm d}_{\rm k}\$ changes; \${\rm F}_{\rm k}\$ and \$\varepsilon_{\rm k}\$ are fixed;


■
Randomized pulse width modulation (RPWM): \${\rm F}_{\rm k}\$ changes; \${\rm d}_{\rm k}\$, and \$\varepsilon_{\rm k}\$ are fixed;


■
Randomized carrier frequency modulation with fixed duty ratio (RCFMFD): \${\rm F}_{\rm k}\$, changes; \${\rm d}_{\rm k}\$ and \$\varepsilon_{\rm k}\$ are fixed;


■
Randomized carrier frequency modulation with variable duty ratio (RCFMVD): \${\rm F}_{\rm k}\$, and \${\rm d}_{\rm k}\$ change; \$\varepsilon_{\rm k}\$ is fixed.

